9","1300":"1300","um 1273":"about 1273","1354":"1354","1308":"1308","1318":"1318","Tadcaster, Yorkshire, England":"Tadcaster, Yorkshire, England","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","Mulgrave Castle, Sandsend Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","North Hampton, Clark, Ohio, Estados Unidos da América":"North Hampton, Clark, Ohio, United States","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mauley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) and Slovak <b>Mašlej</b> or <b>Maslej</b>, Polish <b>Maślej</b>, and probably also of Ukrainian <b>Masliy</b>: derivative of <i>maslo</i> (Polish <i>masło</i>) ‘butter’, applied as an occupational name for a dairyman or perhaps as a nickname (see   Maslak  ).","English: possibly a variant of <b>Mansley</b> with loss of <i>-n-</i>, itself perhaps a variant of <b>Munslow</b>, a habitational name from Munslow in Shropshire. The placename derives from an uncertain initial element + Old English <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Maslak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Kazimierz.","Polish and Jewish (from Poland) (<b>Maślak</b>): nickname from Polish <i>maślak</i>, the name of a species of edible fungus.","Slovak and Czech (<b>Maslák</b>); Polish and Jewish (from Poland) (<b>Maślak</b>); Ukrainian and Croatian; Rusyn (in Poland spelled <b>Maślak</b>): derivative of Slavic <i>maslo</i> (Polish <i>masło</i>) ‘butter’, applied as an occupational name for maker or seller of dairy produce, or perhaps as nickname for someone who was ‘as soft as butter’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave 